That advice is wrong on the key facts. Let me break it down:
“The issue is node-specific” — No. We proved all three masters have NFS timeout errors. Master01 has 178, master02 has 239, master03 has 132. The NFSv3 test succeeded instantly on master03 — the same node where NFSv4.1 was hanging. This isn’t one bad node.
“NFSv4.1 is better for databases” — True in general, but CNPG doesn’t rely on NFS file locking for Postgres consistency. Postgres manages its own WAL and locking internally. The storage is just a data directory. MinIO, Milvus, and every other workload here are the same — none depend on NFSv4 delegations.
“Cordon the bad node” — We already tried that. Cordoned master02, pod landed on master03, same hang. This doesn’t work because it’s not node-specific.
“Change the export policy” — The default export policy is 0.0.0.0/0 with any for RO, RW, and superuser. It’s wide open. The backend_app_access policy is more restrictive. Switching to it would change nothing about the NFSv4.1 hang and could actually break things if the client match doesn’t cover all subnets.
“Reboot master02” — Won’t fix master01 and master03 which have the same issue.
The NFSv3 switch is the right call. The root cause is NFSv4.1 state management between the CoreOS NFS client and your NetApp ONTAP version. Debugging that properly means engaging NetApp support, which isn’t happening before March 18. NFSv3 works, it’s proven, and nothing in your stack needs NFSv4 features.
Patch it, retry CNPG, keep moving.​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​